=========================================================
ABSTRACT CLASSES IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
An Abstract Class is a class that contains at least one Pure Virtual
Function (=0). An object of an abstract class cannot be created.

Syntax:

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED ABSTRACT CLASSES?
=========================================================

1. To achieve Abstraction.
2. To define a common interface.
3. To force derived classes to implement certain functions.
4. To enable Runtime Polymorphism.
5. To provide common functionality to derived classes.

=========================================================
BASIC EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

Shape s;   // ERROR

Reason:
Shape is an Abstract Class.

=========================================================
DERIVED CLASS IMPLEMENTATION
=========================================================

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Drawing Circle\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Shape* ptr = new Circle();

    ptr->draw();
}

Output:
Drawing Circle

=========================================================
HOW DOES AN ABSTRACT CLASS WORK?
=========================================================

Abstract Class:

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

Derived Class:

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Circle";
    }
};

The compiler forces Circle to implement draw().

Otherwise:

class Circle : public Shape
{
};

Compilation Error:

Cannot instantiate abstract class 'Circle'.

=========================================================
ABSTRACT CLASS MEMORY
=========================================================

Abstract classes can have:

• Data Members
• Constructors
• Destructors
• Normal Functions
• Static Members

Only object creation is prohibited.

=========================================================
PROPERTIES OF ABSTRACT CLASSES
=========================================================

1. Contains at least one Pure Virtual Function.
2. Cannot instantiate objects.
3. Can contain implemented functions.
4. Can contain constructors.
5. Can contain destructors.
6. Can contain data members.
7. Can contain static members.
8. Supports Runtime Polymorphism.

=========================================================
CAN ABSTRACT CLASS HAVE DATA MEMBERS?
=========================================================

YES.

class Shape
{
protected:
    int color;

public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

=========================================================
CAN ABSTRACT CLASS HAVE NORMAL FUNCTIONS?
=========================================================

YES.

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;

    void display()
    {
        cout << "Display\n";
    }
};

=========================================================
CAN ABSTRACT CLASS HAVE CONSTRUCTOR?
=========================================================

YES.

class Shape
{
public:
    Shape()
    {
        cout << "Shape Constructor\n";
    }

    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Circle\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Circle c;
}

Output:

Shape Constructor

Reason:
Base class constructor executes first.

=========================================================
CAN ABSTRACT CLASS HAVE DESTRUCTOR?
=========================================================

YES.

Usually make it virtual.

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual ~Shape()
    {
        cout << "Shape Destructor\n";
    }

    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

=========================================================
CAN ABSTRACT CLASS HAVE PURE VIRTUAL DESTRUCTOR?
=========================================================

YES.

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual ~Shape() = 0;
};

Definition is mandatory:

Shape::~Shape()
{
}

Reason:
Destructor must always exist.

=========================================================
CAN ABSTRACT CLASS HAVE STATIC MEMBERS?
=========================================================

YES.

class Shape
{
public:
    static int count;

    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

=========================================================
CAN WE CREATE POINTERS OF ABSTRACT CLASS?
=========================================================

YES.

Shape* ptr;

=========================================================
CAN WE CREATE REFERENCES OF ABSTRACT CLASS?
=========================================================

YES.

Shape& ref = obj;

=========================================================
CAN WE CREATE OBJECT OF ABSTRACT CLASS?
=========================================================

NO.

Shape s;     // ERROR

=========================================================
RUNTIME POLYMORPHISM USING ABSTRACT CLASS
=========================================================

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Circle\n";
    }
};

class Rectangle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Rectangle\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Shape* s1 = new Circle();
    Shape* s2 = new Rectangle();

    s1->draw();
    s2->draw();
}

Output:

Circle
Rectangle

=========================================================
PARTIAL IMPLEMENTATION EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Shape
{
protected:
    int color;

public:
    void setColor(int c)
    {
        color = c;
    }

    virtual void draw() = 0;
};

Derived classes inherit:

• color
• setColor()

But must implement:

draw()

This is Partial Abstraction.

=========================================================
ABSTRACT CLASS VS INTERFACE
=========================================================

Abstract Class
--------------
• Can have data members
• Can have constructors
• Can have implemented methods
• Can maintain state
• Partial abstraction possible

Interface
----------
• Usually only pure virtual functions
• Usually no data members
• Usually no state
• Represents a contract/capability

=========================================================
WHEN TO USE ABSTRACT CLASS?
=========================================================

Use Abstract Class when:

1. Derived classes share common state.
2. Derived classes share common implementation.
3. You want partial abstraction.
4. You want to force implementation of some functions.

Examples:

Shape
Vehicle
Employee
DatabaseConnection

=========================================================
WHEN NOT TO USE ABSTRACT CLASS?
=========================================================

If only behavior contract is required and no shared state or
implementation exists, prefer an Interface.

